│ "llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp"]], "thoughts": "1.    │
│ Understanding the Issue:\nThe transform in                                    │
│ InstCombineSelect::foldSelectEqualityTest folds a nested                      │
│ select-of-equality-tests pattern into a single equality compare of X and Y.   │
│ This is correct for plain icmp eq, but becomes incorrect in the presence of   │
│ the \"samesign\" flag on the icmp. The samesign modifier can cause the icmp   │
│ result to be poison when operands have different signs. In the original       │
│ pattern, the potentially-poison value is masked by select semantics (select   │
│ does not propagate poison if the non-poison arm is chosen). Replacing the     │
│ whole expression with the samesign comparison directly makes the final result │
│ poison in some cases, whereas the original was defined. Alive2 shows a        │
│ concrete counterexample.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\n- The first and only     │
│ transforming point is InstCombinerImpl::foldSelectEqualityTest which replaces │
│ the whole pattern with the icmp samesign eq %X, %Y value.\n- Alive2 error:    │
│ \"Target is more poisonous than source\" with %X = -42, %Y = 0. Source        │
│ returns false (defined), target returns poison. This means the transform is   │
│ not poison-safe.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\n- foldSelectEqualityTest matches │
│ the boolean pattern using m_SpecificICmp(ICMP_EQ, ...) which matches the      │
│ predicate but does not account for the icmp's samesign flag.\n- It then       │
│ returns replaceInstUsesWith(Sel, XeqY) using the existing icmp instruction.   │
│ If XeqY has hasSameSign() set, it may be poison for differing-sign operands,  │
│ even though the original expression masked that poison via selects.\n- Thus,  │
│ the fold is only valid if XeqY is a plain equality icmp (no samesign), or if  │
│ we can otherwise guarantee the icmp cannot be poison. Currently, the code     │
│ does not check this.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s)\n- File:                    │
│ llvm/lib/Transforms/InstCombine/InstCombineSelect.cpp\n- Location: Right      │
│ before returning the XeqY value in foldSelectEqualityTest.\n- Edit: Add a     │
│ guard to bail out if the matched XeqY icmp has the samesign flag.\n\nInserted │
│ code (conceptual):\n\n  // Do not fold through a samesign equality, because   │
│ replacing the whole\n  // expression with a potentially-poison compare can    │
│ make the result\n  // more poisonous than the original (which may have masked │
│ the poison\n  // via selects).\n  if (cast<ICmpInst>(XeqY)->hasSameSign())\n  │
│ return nullptr;\n\nThis is a conservative and correct fix. It avoids creating │
│ a more-poisonous target. An alternative (more aggressive) fix would be to     │
│ build a new plain icmp eq X, Y (without samesign) and replace the select with │
│ it. That would be refinement-safe (less poisonous than source), but requires  │
│ creating a new instruction; the minimal change for safety is to bail out when │
│ samesign is present.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nWe added a safety guard in            │
│ foldSelectEqualityTest to refuse the transformation if the matched X==Y       │
│ comparison carries the samesign flag. This prevents turning a value whose     │
│ poison is masked by selects into a naked poison-producing value, thereby      │
│ fixing the miscompile demonstrated by Alive2. The expected effect is that the │
│ provided reproducer will no longer fold to icmp samesign eq %X, %Y and will   │
│ preserve the original semantics."})                                           │
